			<small class="commentmetadata"><a href="#comment-2219" title="">June 1st, 2009 at 10:03 pm</a> </small>

			<p>Jess - Denver is a great place to ride - jump on the South Platte River bike trail, it&#8217;s a great summer riding path!</p>
<p>Your bike saddle fits your sit-bones, not the other parts of your ass. You&#8217;ll want the saddle such that both your sit-bones are centered on the the saddle, not perched on the outside edges. And no, saddles aren&#8217;t the same on all bikes - there are wider ones (for women who&#8217;ve had kids - Ha!) and skinnier ones for skinny guys whose sit-bones are about an inch apart. And everything in between. BUT the right saddle will likely fit your ass both now and after you lose weight, because your sit-bones aren&#8217;t likely to change their position.</p>
<p>Don&#8217;t delay a bike purchase due to worrying about the saddle. Changing saddles is easier than changing your clothes. When you test ride your bike, if you feel like your ass is falling off the edges of the saddle, have the bike shop swap saddles before you buy. Then after riding for a while if you decide your butt doesn&#8217;t fit right, you can try different ones.</p>

		</li>

	
	
